<h1>COVID-19 Global Intelligence Dashboard</h1>
<div class="subtitle">Power BI Project Report</div>

<table class="meta-table">
<tr><td>Prepared by</td><td>[YOUR NAME]</td></tr>
<tr><td>Course</td><td>[YOUR COURSE NAME]</td></tr>
<tr><td>Batch</td><td>[YOUR BATCH]</td></tr>
<tr><td>Trainer</td><td>[TRAINER NAME]</td></tr>
<tr><td>Date</td><td>June 2026</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tool</td><td>Microsoft Power BI Desktop</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data Source</td><td>Johns Hopkins CSSE (via Kaggle UNCOVER COVID-19 Challenge)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>1. Problem Statement</h2>

<p>The COVID-19 pandemic generated an unprecedented volume of healthcare data across 185+ countries. Government officials, public health agencies, and healthcare administrators faced a critical challenge:</p>

<div class="highlight-box">
<strong>How can we analyze and visualize global COVID-19 pandemic data to identify outbreak trends, compare country-level impacts, and support evidence-based public health decision-making through interactive business intelligence dashboards?</strong>
</div>

<p>Raw datasets in CSV format are difficult to interpret and do not support interactive exploration. There was a need to transform this data into a professional, interactive business intelligence dashboard that enables:</p>

<ul>
<li>Real-time monitoring of key pandemic metrics (cases, deaths, recoveries)</li>
<li>Time-series trend analysis to identify outbreak acceleration or deceleration</li>
<li>Geographic visualization of case distribution across countries</li>
<li>Country-level drill-down analysis for targeted response planning</li>
<li>Mortality and recovery rate comparison to evaluate healthcare effectiveness</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Objectives</h2>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>#</th><th>Objective</th></tr>
<tr><td>O1</td><td>Build an interactive 5-page Power BI dashboard using Johns Hopkins CSSE data</td></tr>
<tr><td>O2</td><td>Design a clean star-schema data model with proper relationships</td></tr>
<tr><td>O3</td><td>Create DAX measures for calculated KPIs (mortality rate, recovery rate, moving averages)</td></tr>
<tr><td>O4</td><td>Enable geographic analysis through map visualizations</td></tr>
<tr><td>O5</td><td>Provide interactive drill-down capability using slicers and cross-filtering</td></tr>
<tr><td>O6</td><td>Deliver data-driven insights and recommendations for stakeholders</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>3. Dataset Description</h2>

<h3>3.1 Source</h3>
<p>Johns Hopkins Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) COVID-19 dataset, obtained through the Kaggle UNCOVER COVID-19 Challenge.</p>

<h3>3.2 Tables Used</h3>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Table</th><th>Source File</th><th>Rows</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>CovidOverTime</strong></td><td>johns-hopkins-covid-19-daily-dashboard-cases-over-time.csv</td><td>23,814</td><td>Daily time-series data per country (Jan–Apr 2020)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>CovidByCountry</strong></td><td>johns-hopkins-covid-19-daily-dashboard-cases-by-country.csv</td><td>185</td><td>Country-level summary with geographic coordinates</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>DateTable</strong></td><td>DAX-generated (CALENDAR function)</td><td>96</td><td>Calendar table for time intelligence functions</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>3.3 Key Columns</h3>

<p><strong>CovidOverTime (Fact Table):</strong> Country, Date, Confirmed, Deaths, New Cases, New Recoveries, Incident Rate</p>
<p><strong>CovidByCountry (Dimension Table):</strong> Country, Latitude, Longitude, Total Confirmed, Deaths, Recovered, Active, ISO 3</p>

<h3>3.4 Data Challenge Identified</h3>

<div class="warning-box">
<strong>Critical Finding:</strong> The <code>recovered</code> and <code>active</code> columns in the time-series dataset (CovidOverTime) were <strong>completely empty</strong> across all 23,814 rows. Recovery data was only available in the country summary table (CovidByCountry — 181 of 185 countries). DAX measures were designed accordingly to reference the correct source table for recovery-related metrics.
</div>

<h2>4. Data Model (Star Schema)</h2>

<div class="model-diagram">                        ┌──────────────────┐
                        │    DateTable     │
                        │  (DAX Calendar)  │
                        │──────────────────│
                        │ Date             │
                        │ Year, Month      │
                        │ Quarter, Week    │
                        └────────┬─────────┘
                                 │ 1 : Many
                                 ▼
  ┌──────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────┐
  │ CovidByCountry   │    │  CovidOverTime   │
  │ (Dimension)      │    │  (Fact Table)    │
  │──────────────────│    │──────────────────│
  │ Country ─────────┼───►│ Country          │
  │ Lat / Long       │    │ Date             │
  │ Total Confirmed  │    │ Confirmed        │
  │ Deaths           │    │ Deaths           │
  │ Recovered ✓      │    │ Recovered ✗      │
  │ Active ✓         │    │ Active ✗         │
  │ ISO 3            │    │ New Cases        │
  └──────────────────┘    │ Incident Rate    │
                          └──────────────────┘
</div>

<p><strong>Relationships:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>DateTable[Date] → CovidOverTime[Date] — One-to-Many</li>
<li>CovidByCountry[Country] → CovidOverTime[Country] — One-to-Many / Many-to-Many</li>
</ol>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h2>5. DAX Measures</h2>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>#</th><th>Measure</th><th>DAX Formula</th><th>Business Purpose</th></tr>
<tr><td>1</td><td>Total Cases</td><td>SUM(CovidOverTime[Confirmed])</td><td>Total confirmed cases globally</td></tr>
<tr><td>2</td><td>Total Deaths</td><td>SUM(CovidOverTime[Deaths])</td><td>Total deaths globally</td></tr>
<tr><td>3</td><td>Total Recovered</td><td>SUM(CovidByCountry[Recovered])</td><td>Total recovered patients (from country summary table)</td></tr>
<tr><td>4</td><td>Total Active</td><td>SUM(CovidByCountry[Active])</td><td>Currently active infections</td></tr>
<tr><td>5</td><td>Daily New Cases</td><td>SUM(CovidOverTime[New Cases])</td><td>Daily pace of new infections</td></tr>
<tr><td>6</td><td>Recovery Rate</td><td>DIVIDE(SUM(Recovered), SUM(Total Confirmed), 0)</td><td>Percentage of patients who recovered</td></tr>
<tr><td>7</td><td>Mortality Rate</td><td>DIVIDE(SUM(Deaths), SUM(Total Confirmed), 0)</td><td>Percentage of patients who died</td></tr>
<tr><td>8</td><td>7-Day Moving Avg</td><td>AVERAGEX(DATESINPERIOD(DateTable[Date], LASTDATE(DateTable[Date]), -7, DAY), [Daily New Cases])</td><td>Smoothed trend — removes daily reporting noise</td></tr>
<tr><td>9</td><td>Case Fatality Rate</td><td>DIVIDE([Total Deaths], [Total Cases], 0)</td><td>Overall virus lethality metric</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>6. Dashboard Pages</h2>

<h3>Page 1 — Executive Overview</h3>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Provide a 10-second snapshot of the global pandemic status for decision-makers.</p>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Visual</th><th>Type</th><th>What It Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td>5 KPI Cards</td><td>Card</td><td>Total Cases (83M), Deaths (5M), Recovered (938K), Active (2M), Recovery Rate (29.95%)</td></tr>
<tr><td>World Map</td><td>Bubble Map</td><td>Geographic distribution of cases — bubble size proportional to case count</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cases Trend</td><td>Area/Line Chart</td><td>Global confirmed cases growth over time (Jan–Apr 2020)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Top 10 Countries</td><td>Horizontal Bar Chart</td><td>Countries with highest confirmed case counts (US leads at 36M+)</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Page 2 — Global Trend Analysis</h3>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Show how the pandemic evolved over time with analytical depth.</p>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Visual</th><th>Type</th><th>What It Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td>Daily New Cases</td><td>Line Chart (Cyan)</td><td>Daily pace of new infections — reveals outbreak waves and acceleration</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cumulative Deaths</td><td>Line Chart (Red)</td><td>Total death toll growing over time — lagging indicator behind cases</td></tr>
<tr><td>7-Day Moving Average</td><td>Line Chart (Amber)</td><td>Smoothed trend line — filters daily reporting noise and weekend effects</td></tr>
<tr><td>Date Slicer</td><td>Slicer (Between)</td><td>Interactive date range selector — enables zoom into specific periods</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Page 3 — Country Intelligence</h3>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Interactive drill-down into individual countries with dynamic filtering.</p>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Visual</th><th>Type</th><th>What It Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td>Country Slicer</td><td>List Slicer (Left sidebar)</td><td>Select any country — all visuals react dynamically via cross-filtering</td></tr>
<tr><td>4 KPI Cards</td><td>Cards</td><td>Country-specific: Total Cases, Deaths, Recovery Rate, Mortality Rate</td></tr>
<tr><td>Treemap</td><td>Treemap</td><td>Proportional case distribution — larger rectangle = more cases</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data Table</td><td>Table</td><td>Detailed breakdown: Country, Cases, Deaths, Recovery Rate, Mortality Rate</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Page 4 — Mortality &amp; Recovery</h3>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Deep comparative analysis of mortality and recovery patterns across countries.</p>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Visual</th><th>Type</th><th>What It Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td>Deaths Bar Chart</td><td>Clustered Bar (Red)</td><td>Top countries ranked by total deaths — US, Italy, Spain lead</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scatter Plot</td><td>Scatter Chart (Cyan)</td><td>Correlation between total cases and deaths — each bubble = 1 country</td></tr>
<tr><td>Matrix Table</td><td>Matrix</td><td>Full numerical comparison with conditional formatting (green→red mortality scale)</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Page 5 — Insights &amp; Recommendations</h3>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Summarize analytical findings and provide actionable recommendations for stakeholders.</p>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Visual</th><th>Type</th><th>What It Shows</th></tr>
<tr><td>Project Overview</td><td>Text Box</td><td>Dashboard methodology and scope description</td></tr>
<tr><td>Key Findings</td><td>Text Box</td><td>7 data-driven insights from the analysis</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data Challenges &amp; Conclusion</td><td>Text Box</td><td>Limitations encountered and professional conclusion</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h2>7. Key Findings</h2>

<ol>
<li><strong>USA recorded the highest cumulative confirmed cases</strong> (36M+), followed by China (7M), Italy (5.7M), Spain (5.5M), and France (3.8M).</li>

<li><strong>Global mortality rate is approximately 6.96%</strong>, with significant variation across countries — ranging from less than 1% to over 15%, suggesting differences in healthcare capacity and reporting standards.</li>

<li><strong>Global recovery rate is 29.95%</strong>, though this figure is limited by incomplete recovery data in the time-series dataset. Only the country summary table contained recovery figures.</li>

<li><strong>Daily new cases showed exponential growth</strong> during March–April 2020, coinciding with the WHO's pandemic declaration on March 11, 2020.</li>

<li><strong>The 7-day moving average</strong> reveals that the true case growth trend accelerated sharply from mid-March, with daily new cases exceeding 100,000 by April 2020.</li>

<li><strong>Strong positive correlation between total cases and total deaths</strong> (visible in scatter plot), though the slope varies by country — indicating differences in healthcare system effectiveness.</li>

<li><strong>Countries with early containment measures</strong> (e.g., China, South Korea) showed relatively lower mortality rates despite high initial case counts, suggesting effective public health interventions.</li>
</ol>

<h2>8. Data Challenges &amp; Limitations</h2>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>Resolution</th></tr>
<tr><td>Recovery data missing in time-series dataset (23,814 rows all empty)</td><td>Could not calculate daily recovery trends over time</td><td>Used country summary table (CovidByCountry) for recovery metrics via targeted DAX measures</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reporting delays and weekend effects</td><td>Artificial spikes and drops in daily case counts</td><td>Applied 7-day moving average to smooth reporting noise</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data covers only Jan–Apr 2020</td><td>Does not capture later waves, Delta/Omicron variants, or vaccination effects</td><td>Noted as limitation; analysis focused on early pandemic dynamics</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inconsistent country reporting standards</td><td>Some countries under-reported cases/deaths, affecting rate calculations</td><td>Acknowledged in findings; mortality rate comparisons interpreted with caution</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>9. Design Choices</h2>

<table class="data-table">
<tr><th>Element</th><th>Choice</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
<tr><td>Background</td><td>Dark theme (#0D1B2A)</td><td>Professional appearance, reduces eye strain, makes data visuals pop — used by Bloomberg, WHO dashboards</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cases color</td><td>Cyan (#00B4D8)</td><td>Neutral healthcare color — informational, not alarming</td></tr>
<tr><td>Deaths color</td><td>Red (#E63946)</td><td>Universal danger/warning color — immediately draws attention to severity</td></tr>
<tr><td>Recovery color</td><td>Green (#2DC653)</td><td>Universal positive/success color — indicates improvement</td></tr>
<tr><td>Moving Avg color</td><td>Amber (#FFD166)</td><td>Contrasts with cyan, suggests analytical caution/insight</td></tr>
<tr><td>Font</td><td>Segoe UI</td><td>Microsoft's modern UI font — clean, professional, excellent readability</td></tr>
<tr><td>Navigation</td><td>Page Navigator buttons</td><td>Enables non-linear exploration — users can jump to any page instantly</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rounded corners</td><td>12px border radius</td><td>Modern design trend — feels premium and less harsh than sharp edges</td></tr>
<tr><td>Drop shadows</td><td>Subtle cyan/red glow</td><td>Adds depth — makes KPI cards feel elevated above the background</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h2>10. Conclusion</h2>

<p>This project demonstrates the application of Microsoft Power BI as a business intelligence tool for healthcare data analytics. By transforming raw Johns Hopkins CSSE CSV datasets into an interactive 5-page dashboard, we achieved the following:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Data Integration:</strong> Successfully combined two datasets (time-series + country summary) using a star-schema model to overcome data completeness challenges. Recovery metrics were sourced from the country summary table after identifying that the time-series dataset contained no recovery data.</li>

<li><strong>Advanced Analytics:</strong> Implemented 9 DAX measures including 7-day moving averages, mortality rates, recovery rates, and case fatality rates to derive meaningful KPIs from raw data.</li>

<li><strong>Interactive Visualization:</strong> Built drill-down capabilities using slicers, cross-filtering, and dynamic KPI cards that respond to user selections — enabling country-level analysis with a single click.</li>

<li><strong>Geographic Intelligence:</strong> Mapped pandemic data across 185 countries using bubble maps, providing immediate visual awareness of geographic spread and concentration.</li>

<li><strong>Actionable Insights:</strong> Identified key pandemic patterns including exponential case growth during March 2020, country-level mortality variations (1%–15%), and the importance of early containment measures.</li>
</ul>

<p>The dashboard provides a scalable template that can be adapted for any public health monitoring scenario, demonstrating how business intelligence tools can support evidence-based decision-making in healthcare emergencies.</p>

